<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica" COLOR="#FF0000">*If HTML and/or <A HREF="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/ubbcode.html" target=_blank>UBB Code</A> are enabled, this means you can use HTML and/or UBB Code in your message.</FONT>
<br>
<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">
<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/Forum21/HTML/001956.html">
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#000050"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#FFFFFF" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">mookus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Well, no you probably dont but, my wizard needs you to. My reasoning is that id like to be able to use area effect spells with my wizard in order to be more mana efficient. Just think how much easier it would be to break a camp if casters could actually use ae spells.<P>Casters have ae dd, clerics get ae heal, druids get ae buffs, bards ae buffs too. Warriors and perhaps all taunters should get a second ae taunt. pls feedback in game regarding this idea.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Zretch</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">AoE taunt is a damage shield.<P>DS your main tank and send him in.  Let the mobs wack at him and build up hate.  Then lay down the AoE.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Kupa</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Try a Fleshripper or some other weapon with an AE proc... throw the damage shield on him for an extra hate bonus.<P>Casters using AE spells are jsut plain dangerous. If all mobs have not yet been engaged you are asking for trouble. AE is nice if it will kill the greenies before they kill you though  <IMG SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/smile.gif"><BR><P>------------------<BR>Kupa FrostHeart<BR>34th Barbarian Warrior<BR>Fennin Ro<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Noreal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Tanks can do multitaunt quite effectively. That is, engage one target, quickly change targets to hit a non-engaged mob when taunt refreshes, taunt it, and go back to the primary target. It takes a bit of dexterity and getting used to the horrible targetting system, but very effective.<P>AE's also do not have high taunt built in, and a damage shield is not necessary. Hate seems to build by them simply beating on the tank, or perhaps by the tank beating on their friend. Either way, with my wizard, I could drop an AE into a pack of mobs if I let the tanks beat on one to about 60% health. I could do it earlier but that would mean I would occasionally get stuff on me.<P>Tip for wizards using AEs: Have shieldskin up (do this anyways, steelskin is VERY nice and quite cheap, your cleric will love you) and be sure to communicate with your party before and after you cast. Perhaps macro a "/g Casting AE" "/g AE cast, nothing on me" and "/g AE cast, pissed something off" so your tanks know what's going on.<P>Tip for warriors in an AE using group: Spread those taunts around. Don't just taunt the main target, hit the others too. This is useful in any multitarget situation as it keeps them off your cleric if he has to start dropping the heals. </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Milena</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">As far as spreading out damage and taunts go, there's an extremely fine line to be walking in a multi-monster situation.  Monsters fight at 100% effectiveness until they run or die, so spreading out the damage more than what is required to easily re-taunt is counter productive.<P>If the group has multiple tanks (with taunt, specifically) it's a good idea to discuss beforehand who be the primary tank.  The group should come up with a plan for dealing with monsters that aggro on casters or clerics so that the group doesn't fall into disarray when this happens.<P>In my opinion it's in everyone's best interest to have the person with the highest actual Taunt skill be the primary re-taunter when stuff attacks your cleric or casters.<P>On the topic of the original post, I would like to see an area-effect taunt for warriors.  Popping this off a couple times during combat (pre-heal) would help greatly in getting stuff off your cleric when they heal.  Same goes for AoE damage spells.<P>Milena<BR>35 warrior on prexus</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Kern the Hunter</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">-I feel that taunting in a multi-target situation is one the few things we Warriors have control on and can become proficient in. If we were to give a Warrior an AE Taunt as a skill it would simply reduce us to pushing a single button then sitting back for a spot of tea while our auto-maton does its stuff for us. Did you ever wonder why the Warrior moves around so much during a Multi-MOB battle. Hes targetting the MOBS by moving to a better position for the action so that they will hit him instead of you.<BR>-Now outside sources such as a proccing(Painbringer,etc) AE weapon is an OK form of AE Taunt for there is some strategy involved in its correct usage.<P>------------------<BR>On the Cazic Thule Server<BR>*Kernan Fenrirson Barbarian Warrior,21st Rank of the Wolves,Naked LongWalk Hating Weilder of the LangSeax."Sons of Fenrir for Halas! For Halas and Glory!"<BR>*Orkus Barbarian Shaman 16th Vision,Spirit Weilding DEMI-GOD in the making.<BR>*Ahirah Dwarven Paladin 9th Tier "Fear me Evil, for I weild the Rantho Rapier!" <P>-"Never argue with an Idiot. First they drag you down to thier level, then beat you with experience." -Unknown<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Fitty</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Certainly this topic has come up before and I still think it's a good idea.  It's not unbalancing in any way that I can see, it would finally give the warrior a distinctive SKILL to separate him from other classes, and it just plain makes sense in the context of the game (warrior shouts, "all you kobolds hit like ERUDITES!")<P>I think that there should be a drawback however... for instance, it could draw unwanted nearby mobs ("did someone just call me an erudite?!?!")<P>------------------<BR>50 Barbarian Warrior, Veeshan (ret)<BR>18 Human Monk, Veeshan (ret)<P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Lasae</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica"><I>The Soluesk Kobold Shaman raises his head...the dim cry of battle echoes through the fiery caves of Nagafen's lair.<P>Perhaps there is trouble the slow thinking Kobold sniffs the air.<P>Human.<P>Wood Elf...no Half-Elf...<P>Ewwww...what in the name of Soluesk is that?<P>Barbarian.<P>The Kobold Shaman quickly summons his pet and casts alacrity on a few passing Lava Duct Crawlers.</I><P><B>Meanwhile...</B><P>Hey...Fitty...I hear somethin.<P>What's that?<P>Sounds like...hm...the slow lumbering gait of a third generation male Shaman Kobold with sixteen lava duct crawlers with alacrity...oh yeah there's a Fire Giant in there too.<P>You sure?  <P>Ya.<P>How?<P>The zone just cleared in under six seconds.  Next time lets not call the Kobolds Erudites ok?<P>But Erudites are so frail and weak like everything in Sol B.<P>/who<P>[50 Warrior Barbarian] Fitty<P>Hey, where'd you go?<P>...Where did I leave that gate potion...<P><I>The rapid sound of advancing lava duct crawlers are pierced by the sound of a male barbarian fleeing for his life.</I><P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Fitty</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Precisely (although somewhat exagerrated.. it would take a SIGNIFICANTLY huge AE to attract more than a couple of LDC's when fighting kobolds... there's only one anywhere near the LDC's).  With great power comes great responsibility.  As with any AE, you have to use it carefully.  I would also suggest that AE taunt breaks mez/stun.<P>------------------<BR>50 Barbarian Warrior, Veeshan (ret)<BR>18 Human Monk, Veeshan (ret)<P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">Raggrok Skullcrusha</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica">ROFL!<P>Erudites... you guys kill me.<P>Yeah I think it's a good idea.<P>Hey, for once I agree with Fitty!<P>But pets still hit harder than I do. =(<P>------------------<BR>-Raggrok Skullcrusha<P>48th Ogre Warrior; RZ<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
